{{short description|A depositional feature as a result of longshore drift, a sandbank that partially or completely closes access to a bay.}}
{{Refimprove|date=September 2018}}
{{-}}
A '''baymouth bar''' is a [[deposition (sediment)|depositional]] feature as a result of [[longshore drift]]. It is a [[bar (landform)|sandbank]] that partially or completely closes access to a [[bay]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/science/sandbar#ref161377 |title=Sandbar (geology) |publisher=Encyclopedia Britannica |accessdate=29 August 2018}}</ref>

These bars usually consist of accumulated gravel and sand carried by the current of longshore drift and deposited at a less turbulent part of the current. Thus, they most commonly occur across artificial bay and river entrances due to the loss of kinetic energy in the current after wave refraction.

