'''Tel Kabri''' ({{lang-he-n|תֵל כַבְרִי}}; {{lang-ar|تَلْ ألْقَهوَة}}, Tell al-Qahweh, "the mound of coffee"{{sfnp|Khalidi|1992|p=28}}) is an [[archaeological]] site of a ''[[Tell (archaeology)|tell]]'' (hill city), containing one of the largest [[Bronze Age|Middle Bronze]] (MB) Age (2,100–1,550 BC) [[Canaan]]ite palaces in ancient Palestine,{{sfnp|Wiener|2013b}} and the largest such palace excavated as of 2014.{{sfnp|Koh|Yasur-Landau|Cline|2014}} Kabri is named for the abundance of its perennial [[Spring (hydrology)|springs]] – as described in the [[#Etymology|Etymology]] section below – the presence of which has led to the site's occupation and use as a water source from the [[Neolithic#Neolithic 3 – Pottery Neolithic (PN)|Pottery Neolithic]] (PN) period (6,400–4,500 BC) to the present day.{{sfnp|Tsuk|2002|p=15}} Located in the Western [[Upper Galilee]], the site was at the height of its power in the MB, controlling much of the surrounding region. Kabri declined as a local power at the end of the MB, but the site continued to be occupied at times, on a much reduced level, up until the [[1948 Arab-Israeli War]].

Since 1957, Tel Kabri has been excavated by the [[Israel Antiquities Authority]] (IAA), formerly the Israel Department of Antiquities and Museums (IDAM), as well as Israeli and American universities.{{sfnp|Stern|Lewinson-Gilboa|Aviram|1993|pp=839–841}} Among the discoveries at the site by the two full-scale archaeological expeditions,{{efn|1= [[#The Tel Kabri Expedition: 1986–1993|The Tel Kabri Expedition]] (1986–1993) and [[#The Tel Kabri Archaeological Project: 2005–ongoing|The Tel Kabri Archaeological Project]] (2005–ongoing) are discussed in detail later in the text.}}  two have attracted particular attention from the archaeological community. The first finding to come to international attention was the discovery of [[Minoan civilization|Minoan]]-style [[fresco]]es in the palace at Kabri.{{sfnp|Cline|Yasur-Landau|Goshen|2011|p=245}} {{as of|2015}}, these are the only Minoan-style frescoes ever discovered in Israel.{{sfnp|Science Daily|2009}} Second, in 2013, the Tel Kabri Archaeological Project uncovered the oldest and largest known palatial [[wine cellar]] in the [[Ancient Near East]] in Kabri's palace.{{sfnp|Burrows|2013}}

==Etymology==
{{as of|2015}}, the original Canaanite name of Tel Kabri is unknown.{{efn|1= Tel Kabri, as the name suggests is a ''[[Tell (archaeology)|tel]]'', a type of mound found from the [[Balkans]] to the [[Punjab region|Punjab]] that is created as a result of the destruction of mudbrick from repeated different periods of occupation of a site.{{sfnp|Cline|2009|pp=21-22}}}} Aharon Kempinski hypothesised that Kabri might have been the same city as Rehov, referred to in the [[Execration Texts]], an [[Ancient Egypt]]ian list of enemy polities.{{sfnp|Kempinski|2002b|p=452}} [[Amihai Mazar]] once believed that Tel Kabri – or the site of [[Rehov|Tel Rehov]] – might be the Rehov from the Execration Texts, or Tel Kabri might be a different Rehov mentioned in topographic lists by [[Pharaoh]] [[Thutmose III]].{{sfnp|Mazar|1999|p=4}} No definitive evidence has been found to support any of these hypotheses. By the [[Iron Age Levant|Iron Age]], 1200-500BC (IA), the site is known to have been called Rehov, and this continued into the [[Phoenicia#High point: 1200–800 BC|Phoenician]] period – a period of Phoenician dominance over the area, which was concurrent with the Iron Age.{{sfnp|Stern|Lewinson-Gilboa|Aviram|1993|p=841}}

Early in the [[Phoenicia under Roman rule|Roman Period]] (64 BC–500s AD), the town of Kabrita had been established to the east of the tel.{{sfnp|Stern|Lewinson-Gilboa|Aviram|1993|p=841}} The site is mentioned in the 3rd century [[Mosaic of Rehob]], as marking one of the northernmost bounds of Jewish resettlement after their return from [[Babylonian exile]].<ref>Raphael Frankel and [[Israel Finkelstein]], ''The Northwest Corner of Eretz-Israel in the Baraita ‘Boundaries of Eretz-Israel’'' Cathedra: For the History of Eretz Israel and its Yishuv (vol. 27), 1983, pp. 39–46. (See: {{cite journal |last=Finkelstein |first=Israel |title='The Northwest Corner of Eretz-Israel' in the Baraita 'Boundaries of Eretz-Israel' |journal=Cathedra: For the History of Eretz Israel and its Yishuv |volume=27 |issue= |pages=39–46 |jstor=23398920|date=1983|registration=yes }}).</ref> Kabrita became the Arab village of el-Kabira, which by the late 1200s AD was called al-Kabrah by the Arabs and Le Quiebre by the [[Kingdom of Jerusalem#The Kingdom of Acre|Crusader]]s who controlled the area at the time. By 1880, both the village and the ruins on the tel had come to be associated and bear the same names.{{sfnp|Guérin|1880|p=32}} Al-Kabrah eventually became [[al-Kabri]],{{sfnp|Barag|1979|p=203}} and this name lasted until the [[1948 Arab-Israeli War]] when the village was depopulated.{{sfnp|Anon|1988|p=49}} Both the post-war kibbutz, [[Kabri, Israel|Kabri]], on whose grounds the archaeological site is located, and the tel itself, are named for al-Kabri.{{sfnp|Anon|1988|p=49}} The name of Kabrita, and the later names, were derived from the triconsonantal [[Semitic root#Triconsonantal roots|Semitic root]], כבר, meaning 'great or powerful', in reference to the plentiful water from Kabri's springs.{{sfnp|Kempinski|2002b|p=452}}

==Geography==
Tel Kabri is at the eastern end of the Western Galilee coastal plain, located on the grounds of Kibbutz Kabri. It is less than {{convert|5|km|mi}} from the [[Mediterranean Sea|sea]], and the [[Ga'aton River]] is nearby to the south, with the closest major city being [[Nahariyya]] to the west. The [[Tell (archaeology)|tel]] is home to four springs, Ein Shefa, Ein Giah, Ein Tzuf, and Ein ha-Shayara.{{sfnp|Tsuk|2002|p=15}} It is these springs that have brought people to Kabri since the Neolithic.{{sfnp|Tsuk|2002|p=15}}

Natural resources such as trees on the hills to the east and stone quarries near the coast were important for the inhabitants of the site. Kabri's height is partly a result of human activity: Over the centuries, material remains created layers that built up thetel.{{sfnp|Cline|2009|pp=21-22}} During Kempinski's excavations, it was found that the original surface in the Neolithic would have been up to {{convert|5.5|m|ft}} lower than the present surface.{{sfnp|Horowitz|2002|p=8}}

==History==

The tel and its surrounding area have been inhabited since the [[Neolithic#Neolithic 3 .E2.80.93 Pottery Neolithic .28PN.29|Pottery Neolithic]] (PN).{{efn|1= 6,400–4,500 BC}}  Kabri was at the height of its power in the MB, when the polity there controlled a significant portion of the Upper Galilee. After the MB, Tel Kabri was occupied by later peoples – though on a much reduced scale – up to the founding of the State of Israel, when the kibbutz of Kabri was created.{{sfnp|Stern|Lewinson-Gilboa|Aviram|1993|p=839}}

===Pre-Palatial===

The area of Kabri was first settled during the PN by members of the [[Yarmoukian]] culture.{{sfnp|Marder|al.|2002|p=305}} In the early [[Chalcolithic]] period (4500–3500 BC), Kabri was a major centre of the [[Wadi Raba]] culture. In the Early Bronze (EB) Age (3500-2100 BC), there was a town on the side of the tel that was destroyed as part of the region-wide [[societal collapse|systems collapse]] that characterised the EB collapse.{{efn|1= The Early Bronze Age collapse is the event that is traditionally used to mark the end of the EB and the beginning of MB. The "collapse" was an abrupt end to the material culture – such as pottery and architecture – that is identified with the EB civilisations of the [[Aegean Civilization|Aegean]], [[Bronze Age Anatolia#Early Bronze Age|Anatolia]] and the [[Bronze Age Levant#Bronze Age|Levant]] and the beginning of a period marked by the prevalence of so-called palatial society. {{As of|2015}} there is no accepted explanation for this sudden change.}}  In the early and middle MB I, Tel Kabri – along with [[Tel Megiddo|Megiddo]], [[Tel Afek|Aphek]], and [[Acre, Israel#Antiquity|Akko]] – was one of the earliest cities in the Levant to rebuild its fortifications following the EB collapse.{{sfnp|Kempinski|1992|p=127}} The new city was confined to the northern part of the earlier EB tel.{{sfnp|Yasur-Landau|Ebeling|Mazow|2011|p=70}}

===Palatial===

Prior to the ongoing excavations at Kabri that began in 2005,{{efn|1= {{as of|2015}}, excavations are ongoing.}}  archaeologists thought that there was only one palace at the site,{{efn|1= A palace that had been found by Aharon Kempinski during the [[#The Tel Kabri Expedition: 1986–1993|Tel Kabri Expedition of 1986–1993]].}}  and that it was built in the period between the late MB I (2200–1950 BC) and MB IIA (1950–1700 BC). It was also thought that the MB I period had been a transition phase. However, the palace found by Kempinski has been dated to the MB IIB (1700–1550 BC), and in 2010, a second, earlier, palace – an MB IIA palace{{efn|1= MB I and MB IIA are interchangeable terms. This palace is hereinafter referred to as the earlier palace.}}  – was identified beneath the MB IIB palace.{{efn|1= Hereinafter referred to as the later palace.}}  The remains of the earlier MB IIA palace appear to show that it was expanded to create the later MB IIB palace. The discovery of the earlier palace pushes the dates for palatial occupation of the site to the MB IIA, 150 years earlier than originally believed. The earlier MB IIA palace may have been "the most impressive structure in the Upper Galilee" at the time, and was possibly the oldest palace in Canaan.{{sfnp|Yasur-Landau|Cline|2010|p=8}}

Earlier still, at the transition between the MB I and MB II, a large-scale restructuring programme was undertaken in a possible effort to transform Kabri into an idealised Syrian-style city – a powerful city-state centred around a magnificent and well-fortified palace.{{sfnp|Yasur-Landau|Ebeling|Mazow|2011|p=70}} The area was fortified, and an additional {{convert|25|ha|m2}} were enclosed within a large glacis, a type of earthwork fortification that was {{convert|50|m|ft}} wide with a stone core and that encircled the tel as it appears today. The glacis was topped by mudbrick and stone.{{sfnp|Issar|Zohar|2004|p=147}} There was an MB I palace and this was expanded into the MB II palaces.{{sfnp|Yasur-Landau|Cline|2010|p=8}} This restructuring programme resulted in some parts of the tel being flattened out and a large portion of the population having to find new homes in the city, as a result of part of the MB IIA palace – along with certain parts of the rampart – being built in an area previously occupied by private houses.{{sfnp|Yasur-Landau|Ebeling|Mazow|2011|p=72}} Kabri's ancillary sites (such as [[Achziv]] and [[Avdon]]) were also built up, and migration from the hinterland to Kabri – and its secondary sites – increased dramatically as a result of these projects.{{sfnp|Yasur-Landau|Ebeling|Mazow|2011|pp=72–73}} Kabri became the capital of a major polity, with the newly expanded MB II palace at its centre.{{sfnp|Marom|al.|2014|p=63}}

At the peak of its power, Kabri may have controlled a domain that stretched from [[Mount Carmel]] in the south to the [[Sulam range]] in the north, with as many as 31 vassal sites and 30,000 subjects.{{sfnp|Cline|Yasur-Landau|2007|p=162}} Kempinski hypothesised that Kabri might be the Bronze Age settlement of Rehov, a polity mentioned in the Execration Texts and the biblical [[Book of Joshua]].{{sfnp|Stern|Lewinson-Gilboa|Aviram|1993|p=839}}During this period, Kabri maintained significant contacts with neighbouring regions in the form of trade and exchange of ideas.{{sfnp|Cline|Yasur-Landau|Pierce|2008|p=62}}

Counting the MB I, MB IIA, and MB IIB stages, the palace was continuously occupied for three centuries. This is longer than any other palace in ancient Israel.{{sfnp|Yasur-Landau|Cline|2010|p=8}}

===Post-Palatial===
{{details|topic=the modern history of the village of al-Kabri and the kibbutz of Kabri|Kabri, Israel#Modern history}}
[[File:AcreNE1799.jpg|thumb|[[Sidon Eyalet|Ottoman period]] French survey map from 1799 showing the Upper Galilee. Kabri's springs are shown as being exploited by Akko.]]
By 1500 BC, the site was abandoned for reasons unknown as of the 2015.{{sfnp|Burrows|2013}} Some time after the abandonment, during the Late Bronze (LB) Age (1550–1200 BC), a small village occupied the tel.{{sfnp|Stern|Lewinson-Gilboa|Aviram|1993|p=841}}
In the Iron Age, the site was reoccupied by Greek mercenaries under hire from the Phoenician city-state of [[Tyre, Lebanon#Early history|Tyre]]. The mercenaries were based in a citadel there.{{sfnp|Yasur-Landau|Cline|2005|p=2}} Close to the citadel, in the Iron Age and Phoenician periods, the later Phoenician city of Rehov was sited at Kabri. The Phoenician town was fortified by a [[casemate]] wall. This town was destroyed by the armies of the [[Neo-Babylonian]] king, [[Nebuchadnezzar II]] around 585 BC, and his rule was extended over [[Phoenicia under Babylonian rule|Phoenicia]].{{sfnp|Kempinski|Niemeier|1994|p=35*}} After this destruction, the town was rebuilt and this new town grew during the [[Achaemenid Phoenicia|Persian period]] (538–332 BC). Remains from this time have been found near the tel's spring of Ein Shefa.{{sfnp|Stern|Lewinson-Gilboa|Aviram|1993|p=841}} Habitation at the tel itself ends at this point. Early in the [[Phoenicia under Hellenistic rule|Hellenistic period]] (332–64 BC), the ruins of the Iron Age citadel were used for burials, but the tel was not resettled until the [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] period (1517-1917 AD).{{sfnp|Lehmann|2002|p=87}}

Some time during the [[Phoenicia under Roman rule|Early Roman period]], a Jewish settlement is mentioned, named Kabrita,{{sfnp|Aviram|1997|p=23}} located east of the tel in the area that was occupied by the later Arab village, eventually named al-Kabri.{{sfnp|Stern|Lewinson-Gilboa|Aviram|1993|p=839}} Kabri, appearing under the name of al-Kabrah, is mentioned in the last [[hudna]], or peace treaty, between the [[Kingdom of Jerusalem]]{{efn|1= Which by that point had been reduced to a remnant based out of Akko (called Acre).}}  and the [[Mamluks]].{{efn|1= A [[Turkic peoples|Turkic]] sultanate based in Egypt which ruled most of the Levant at the time}}  In the treaty, the village and its surrounding fields, are shown as belonging to the ruler of Akko.{{sfnp|Barag|1979|p=203}}

In addition to al-Kabri which is located east of the site, during the Ottoman Period, two additional Arab villages were founded on the actual site – [[Al-Nahr|en-Nahr]] and [[al-Tall, Acre|et-Tell]] – in the southern and western portions of the tel, respectively.{{sfnp|Stern|Lewinson-Gilboa|Aviram|1993|p=839}} All three villages were close to the major springs, but during most of their existence, they were sparsely populated – in the low hundreds. Al-Kabri appears as ''Kabli'' and En-Nahr appears as ''el-Qahweh'' in the first topographic map of the region made in 1799 by [[Napoleon]]'s cartographer, [[Pierre Jacotin]]. This same map does not show Et-Tell, and only shows a mill in that location.{{sfnp|Karmon|1960|p=160}} Et-Tell does appear in the later [[Palestine Exploration Fund]] map of 1880,{{sfnp|Karmon|1960|p=160}} and is talked about by [[Victor Guérin]] in his travelogue of the area, published that same year, which described all three villages.{{sfnp|Guérin|1880|pp=31-33, 46, 50}} Karmon hypothesised that the new village of et-Tell might have been founded by villagers from el-Qahweh as a home for mill workers.{{sfnp|Karmon|1960|p=246}} The three villages existed up to the 1948 Arab-Israeli War when they were depopulated.{{sfnp|Morris|2004|pp=253-254}}

Much of Kabri's recorded history also deals with its springs and, starting in the Hellenistic period, the springs' relationship to the city of [[Akko]].{{sfnp|Tsuk|2002|pp=15-17}} The springs of Kabri have fed Akko for centuries, and aqueducts have been built from Kabri to Akko by local rulers.{{sfnp|Tsuk|2002|p=17}} In the Hellenistic period, an aqueduct was constructed at Kabri,{{sfnp|Frankel|2002|pp=82-87}} and another was built during the governorship of [[Jezzar Pasha]], the Ottoman ruler of [[Acre, Israel#Ottoman era|Akko]] who also ruled the [[Eyalet of Sidon]] (1775-1804).{{efn|1= An ''[[eyalet]]'' was an Ottoman administrative division corresponding to a province. Most of the Galilee, including Kabri, fell under the Eyalet of Sidon.}}  Later, a new aqueduct was built by Jezzar's successor, [[Suleiman Pasha(Acre)|Sulaymán Páshá]]{{efn|1= Jezzar's aqueduct had been destroyed by the military forces of [[Napoleon Bonaparte]].}}  in the Ottoman Period, and this aqueduct functioned up until the 1948 Arab-Israeli War.{{sfnp|Tsuk|2002|p=18}} Portions of the structure still stand today.{{sfnp|Kahanov|2011|p=104}}

Following the War, the tel was incorporated into the grounds of Kibbutz Kabri and was made into agricultural land. Soon after, the ancient remains of the site were rediscovered and on-and-off archaeological work began which continues to the present day alongside the agricultural work of the kibbutz.
{{Clear}}

==Archaeology==
[[File:TelKabriRegion.png|thumb|250px|Tel Kabri in relation to old and new settlements]]
Tel Kabri has been a subject of archaeological study since 1957, following the discovery of Late Neolithic vessels at the site in 1956 by members of the kibbutz.{{sfnp|Prausnitz|1959|pp=268–269}} After 1961, most of the focus on the site shifted to Bronze Age material remains. [[Archaeological survey|Surveys]] and excavations have taken place at the site to explore its past.{{sfnp|Kempinski|2002a|pp=2–3}}

Tel Kabri is a multi-period site, meaning that it has layers, or "strata", of occupation dating from different time periods. The tel itself operates as an agricultural area of Kibbutz Kabri, and certain layers have been subject to damage as a result of agriculture activity.{{Sfnm|Kempinski|2002a|1p=4|Kempinski|2002c|2p=35}}

The tel is located on the grounds of the kibbutz, and contains the remains of the Canaanite city from the MB period and the partially excavated later Iron Age citadel. Tel Kabri is the only Canaanite city that can be excavated in its entirety because no other city with monumental architecture was built on the site after the MB city.{{sfnp|Science Daily|2009}} In 2013, it was estimated that the palace would have occupied {{convert|6100|m2|acres|abbr=on}},{{sfnp|Yasur-Landau|al.|2013|p=10}} and in 2006, it was estimated that the ancient city as a whole would have occupied {{convert|4|ha|acres|abbr=on|0}}.{{sfnp|Cline|Yasur-Landau|2006b|p=37}}

As a result of farming and erosion, Stratum 1 of the tel, the uppermost layer, has been heavily damaged.{{efn|1= Strata (sing. stratum) are layers of stratigraphy. Typically strata arranged in descending order, so Stratum 1 is physically on top of Stratum 2, which is in turn over Stratum 3, and so on. See the following section for a brief explanation of stratigraphy.}}  Prior to agricultural activities by the ''[[kibbutz]]niks'' in 1976, there still existed large towers on the tel, which may have been gates.{{sfnp|Kempinski|2002c|p=35}} The entire site is cut across by a [[Mandatory Palestine|British Mandate]] period (1920–1948 AD) road that originally led from the coastal city of [[Nahariyya]] to the ''[[moshav]]'' of [[Me'ona]].{{sfnp|Kempinski|2002a|p=1}}  Most of the tel was also covered over with a metre of sterile top-soil (containing no archaeological remains) laid down for the purpose of farming by the kibbutz between Kempinski's excavations ending in 1993 and the beginning of the ongoing expedition in 2005. According to Tel Kabri Archaeological Project co-Director Assaf Yasur-Landau: "The city's preservation enables us to get a complete picture of political and social life in the Canaanite period. We can reveal whether or not it had a central government, whether taxes were levied, what sort of agriculture there was and how politics were conducted at the time."{{sfnp|Science Daily|2009}}

===Stratigraphy===
{{details|topic=stratigraphy and its uses in archaeology|Stratigraphy (archaeology)}}
Kempinski identified twelve stratigraphic layers at Tel Kabri. Stratigraphy is the layering of soil with the more recent soil layers higher up and the older soil layers further down. Archaeologists and geologists use stratigraphy to date artefacts found in the soil relative to each other.{{efn|1= See [[Relationship (archaeology)]] for further information on how the relationships between archaeological finds are determined.}}  The artefacts – in particular, [[sherd]]s of pottery – can, in turn, be used to date the layer of soil and its contents to a specific date range.{{efn|1= See ''[[Seriation (archaeology)]]'' for an explanation on how archaeologists can use pottery to create a timeline for the past.}}  The 1986-1993 Tel Kabri Expedition did not find a continuous stratigraphic sequence in any one excavation trench, and so Kempinski based the identification of the layers at Tel Kabri on finds in different areas.{{sfnp|Kempinski|2002a|p=4}} He arranged the layers as follows:{{sfnp|Kempinski|2002a|pp=4–5}}

