{{otheruses|Tilbury (disambiguation)}}
{{orphan|date=November 2013}}
'''Tilbury Town''' is a [[fictional]] American town which serves as the location for many works by the [[United States|American]] poet [[Edwin Arlington Robinson]].<ref name="robinson1953">Robinson, Edwin Arlington (1953).''Tilbury Town: selected poems of Edwin Arlington Robinson.'' Macmillan, ASIN: B0007DX44O</ref>  

The small [[New England]] village was modeled after [[Gardiner, Maine]] where Robinson grew up.<ref name="zeitlow1967">Zietlow, Paul (1967). The Meaning of Tilbury Town: Robinson as a Regional Poet.  ''[[The New England Quarterly]]'' Vol. 40, No. 2 (Jun., 1967), pp. 188-211</ref><ref name="free 1966">Free, William J. (1966). E. A. Robinson's Use of Emerson ''[[American Literature (journal)|American Literature]]'' Vol. 38, No. 1 (Mar., 1966), pp. 69-84.</ref><ref name="comas">Comas, Beatrice H. (Jul. 9, 1977) [https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Y2AgAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s2UFAAAAIBAJ&pg=1408,1012634 Edward Alington Robinson, poet from 'Tilbury Town."] ''[[Lewiston Evening Journal]]''</ref>

